solutionCode.javascript:
    ```javascript
function gcdOfStrings(str1, str2) {
    if (str1 + str2 !== str2 + str1) {
        return "";
    }
    const gcd = (a, b) => b === 0 ? a : gcd(b, a % b);
    return str1.substring(0, gcd(str1.length, str2.length));
}
```


    The algorithm first checks if the concatenation of the strings is equal in both the orders (str1 + str2  and  str2 + str1). If they are not equal, that means there is no common substring that divides both str1 and str2, so an empty string is returned.

If the concatenation is equal, the algorithm computes the greatest common divisor (GCD) of the length of both strings using the Euclidean algorithm. The common substring is a prefix of length GCD, so the function returns the substring from starting index (0) to the GCD value.

